## Phase 1: Global Evidence of Micronutrient Deficiency  

### 1.1 Global Nutrient Inadequacy (Harvard T.H. Chan, 2024)  

In 2024, researchers at **Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health** published a global dietary assessment covering **185 countries**, revealing the true scale of micronutrient inadequacy.

Key findings show that **more than half of the world’s population** fails to meet recommended intake levels for essential micronutrients, even when caloric intake is sufficient.

**Most widespread deficiencies worldwide:**

- Iron  
- Calcium  
- Vitamin C  
- Vitamin E  

| Micronutrient | Estimated Population with Inadequate Intake |
|--------------|---------------------------------------------|
| Iodine | ~68% |
| Vitamin E | ~67% |
| Calcium | ~66% |
| Iron | ~65% |

These results redefine malnutrition as a **nutritional quality crisis**, not merely a problem of food scarcity.

*Source: The Lancet Global Health (2024)*  

